      People are worried about oil stock buybacks
   =20
 =20

Here is a theory you could have:
=09The world runs on oil right now, demand for oil is high, the price of oi=
l is high, and getting oil out of the ground is lucrative.=09In X years =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0pick a number =E2=80=94=C2=A0the world will not run on oil, bec=
ause the environmental effects of burning oil are bad, and eventually, thro=
ugh some combination of better green-energy technology, consumer demand and=
 government regulation, the world will stop burning oil.=09Therefore the oi=
l-drilling business will produce a series of cash flows that is large now a=
nd will, over the next X years, decline to zero.

You don=E2=80=99t have to believe this theory, but something like it seems =
to be pretty=C2=A0popular. In particular, environmental, social and governa=
nce investors often express some version of this; they talk about the need =
to transition to green energy and question the long-term viability of fossi=
l fuels.
I suspect that many oil-and-gas executives and investors don=E2=80=99t=C2=
=A0believe this theory, but what if they do?=C2=A0If you are the chief exec=
utive officer of an oil company, and you believe this, what should you=C2=
=A0do=C2=A0about it? What is the best way to create long-term value for you=
r shareholders? Here are=C2=A0three imaginable answers:
=09Do what you=E2=80=99ve always done.=C2=A0Drill lots of oil, acquire new =
leases, explore the deep ocean,=C2=A0make long-term investments in drilling=
 technology, keep being an oil company, hope it all works out.=C2=A0=09Pivo=
t to renewables.
  [1]
 Drill oil for now, but make your long-term investments in green energy; bu=
ild wind farms or drill geothermal wells=C2=A0or whatever, so that in X yea=
rs, when the world stops using oil, you will be able to sell whatever it do=
es=C2=A0use.=09Drill the oil you=E2=80=99ve got, but plan for decline. Stop=
 making lots of new long-term investments in oil fields. Maximize current c=
ash flow, and spend it on stock buybacks. Eventually, in X years, your cash=
 flows will be zero, and you will close up shop gracefully. But in the mean=
time there is money coming in, and rather than waste it on drilling new oil=
 fields, you give it back to shareholders.

Answer 1 seems=C2=A0wrong, on this theory: If you make long-term oil invest=
ments, and oil is doomed in the long term, then your investments are wastef=
ul. You are taking profits that belong to shareholders and wasting them on =
inertia.
Answer 2 seems fine! The idea here is that you are an=C2=A0energy=C2=A0comp=
any, not an=C2=A0oil=C2=A0company, and your expertise in energy makes you b=
est positioned to find the energy of the future.
  [2]
=C2=A0You have geologists and engineers and energy economists and a lot of =
money; you might be better at developing green energy than some inexperienc=
ed green-energy startup would be. I think this is=C2=A0debatable=C2=A0=E2=
=80=94=C2=A0if you are an oil-company CEO, and you grew up around oil, you =
might be biased against green tech and more comfortable with oil =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0but certainly possible.
Answer 3 also seems fine! The idea here is that your company got into busin=
ess, 100 years ago or whatever, to do a thing: drill oil. You did the thing=
 successfully and it made a lot of money. Now the money pours in, but the t=
hing is in decline; there is a natural lifespan to your business, and the e=
nd is visible. Rather than fight embarrassingly against the end, you take t=
he cash that is still coming in and you give it to your shareholders.
  [3]
=C2=A0
What do they do with it? Buy groceries or yachts, I suppose, but=C2=A0they=
=C2=A0could also invest it. They could invest it in green energy companies?=
 Here the idea is that=C2=A0other=C2=A0companies =E2=80=94=C2=A0green-energ=
y startups, utility companies, I guess=C2=A0oil companies other than you =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0will be=C2=A0better=C2=A0at building green energy than you a=
re. (Or: The idea is that your shareholders will be better at allocating ca=
pital to green-energy projects=C2=A0than you, an oil-company CEO, are.) You=
 are an oil company, your employees and equipment and expertise are all opt=
imized for finding and drilling oil, you have no great advantage in buildin=
g wind farms and a sort of institutional bias against it. Give the money to=
 shareholders and let them fund the best wind farmers they=C2=A0can find, i=
nstead of asking them to trust you to build a wind farm.
Anyway here is a Wall Street Journal report about  how oil-and-gas sharehol=
ders want Answer 3:

Oil-and-gas companies have built up a mountain of cash with few precedents =
in recent history. Wall Street has a few ideas on how to spend it=E2=80=94a=
nd new drilling isn=E2=80=99t near the top of the list. ...
Even as an uncertain economic outlook has weighed on crude in 2023, making =
the energy sector the S&P 500=E2=80=99s worst performer, cash has continued=
 flowing. Companies that previously chased growth and funneled money into s=
peculative drilling investments, weighing down their stocks, have instead t=
ried to appease Wall Street by boosting dividends and repurchasing shares.=
=C2=A0
The cash has helped make up for stock prices that often seesaw alongside vo=
latile commodity markets. Steady returns also buoy an industry with an unce=
rtain long-term outlook as governments, markets and the global economy grad=
ually shift toward cleaner energy.=C2=A0=E2=80=A6
President Biden has called on producers to ramp up output in a bid to lower=
 prices at the pump. =E2=80=9CThese balance sheets make clear that there is=
 nothing stopping oil companies from boosting production except their own d=
ecision to pad wealthy shareholder pockets and then sit on whatever is left=
,=E2=80=9D White House Assistant Press Secretary Abdullah Hasan said. ...
=E2=80=9CU.S. oil-and-gas producers are less focused on capital spending th=
an they have been in years,=E2=80=9D said Mark Young, a senior analyst at E=
valuate Energy.=C2=A0
The cash buildup owes itself to other factors as well. Many companies have =
paid off debt racked up during growth mode, when they dug much of the top-t=
ier territory for wells. While some companies have pledged huge sums to car=
bon-capture technology or hydrogen production, clean-energy investment has =
been slowed by lower expected returns and the wait for yet-to-be-finalized =
regulations in Mr. Biden=E2=80=99s climate package.=C2=A0

I should add that, like, pure-play wind-farm companies might have another a=
dvantage over oil companies in building wind farms: Their cost of capital m=
ight be lower. ESG=C2=A0investors tend to reward companies with good ESG sc=
ores (like green-energy companies)=C2=A0and penalize companies with bad ESG=
 scores (like oil companies). This can have the (intended) result of loweri=
ng the cost of capital of green companies (lots of ESG investors want to bu=
y their stock) and raising the cost of capital of polluting companies (nobo=
dy wants their stock). We  talked a few weeks ago about a paper on =E2=80=
=9CCounterproductive Sustainable Investing: The Impact Elasticity of Brown =
and Green Firms,=E2=80=9D by Samuel Hartzmark and Kelly Shue, arguing that =
this has the effect of=C2=A0making polluting companies more short-term-focu=
sed:=C2=A0If your cost of capital is high, near-term projects are worth rel=
atively more and long-term projects are worth relatively less, so you will =
focus on the short term. Hartzmark and Shue argue that in particular this m=
eans that polluting oil companies who get little love from ESG investors wi=
ll decide to drill more oil to maximize short-term cash flows, but it does =
also suggest that polluting oil companies might=C2=A0decide to do less oil=
=C2=A0exploration=C2=A0and other long-term oil-focused investment, and spen=
d more of their cash flows on stock buybacks. Your model could be something=
 like =E2=80=9CESG lowers the cost of capital of green firms and raises the=
 cost of capital of polluting firms, to encourage green firms to invest mor=
e for the long term and encourage polluting firms not=C2=A0to plan to stick=
 around.=E2=80=9D And then a lot of stock buybacks from oil firms would be =
a reasonable ESG outcome.
I should also say that the specific story here =E2=80=94=C2=A0oil companies=
 are buying back stock rather than drilling more wells =E2=80=94=C2=A0does =
not=C2=A0require=C2=A0either an ESG perspective or a long-term view that oi=
l is on the decline. =E2=80=9CLast time oil prices were high, oil companies=
 overinvested in drilling, and then prices crashed and investors lost money=
=E2=80=9D is also a perfectly reasonable explanation.
One thing that I think, though,=C2=A0when people get angry about stock buyb=
acks generally, is that there are probably a lot of industries like this? =
=E2=80=9CWe do a business, it makes money, we have a lot of money, but even=
tually this business will end and we won=E2=80=99t be good at whatever repl=
aces it, so we might as well give the money back to shareholders so they=C2=
=A0can recycle it, instead of na=C3=AFvely=C2=A0reinvesting in a business t=
hat can=E2=80=99t last forever,=E2=80=9D is probably the right way to think=
 about things a lot of the time!

