   =20
 =20

We   talked last Thursday about two theories of banking, which I called The=
ory 1 and Theory 2. Theory 1 is that banks borrow short to lend long: Bank =
deposits are short-term funding, they get paid a variable market rate of in=
terest, and they can disappear overnight if depositors worry about a bank=
=E2=80=99s stability or just get a better deal elsewhere. Theory 2 is that =
banks actually borrow long to lend long: Bank deposits are part of a long-t=
erm relationship, and much of what banks do =E2=80=94=C2=A0build branches, =
cross-sell products, offer ATMs and online banking =E2=80=94=C2=A0is design=
ed to make those deposits sticky, so that their cost=C2=A0doesn=E2=80=99t=
=C2=A0go up when interest rates go up. Theory 2 is the traditional theory o=
f banking; it=E2=80=99s why there are branches. Theory 1 is the standard th=
eory of modern capital markets; it=E2=80=99s why, when Silicon Valley Bank =
failed due to taking too much interest-rate risk, lots of people were like =
=E2=80=9Chow did they not see that coming=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cwhy didn=E2=
=80=99t they hedge?=E2=80=9D
Part of my goal on Thursday was to try to answer those questions, to sugges=
t=C2=A0that Theory 2 really is kind of how banks (and bank regulators) thin=
k about the problem. (=E2=80=9CWhy didn=E2=80=99t they hedge their interest=
-rate risk?=E2=80=9D Well, they had long-duration liabilities, in the form =
of deposits, and they matched them with long-duration assets, in the form o=
f Treasury and agency bonds, so they=C2=A0were=C2=A0hedged; they just got t=
he duration of their deposits wrong.)
And part of my goal was to=C2=A0think about why Theory 2 stopped working in=
 2023, why deposits=C2=A0weren=E2=80=99t=C2=A0sticky, why banks like Silico=
n Valley Bank and First Republic Bank faced massive runs and disappeared wh=
en rates went up. My speculations included better availability of informati=
on (bank deposits used to be sticky in part because it was harder to pay at=
tention to them), a more widespread mark-to-market financial culture, the h=
angover of 2008, and the decline of relationship businesses generally:
In a world of electronic communication and global supply chains and work-fr=
om-home and the gig economy, business relationships are less sticky and =E2=
=80=9CI am going to go into my bank branch and shake the hand of the manage=
r and trust her with my life savings=E2=80=9D doesn=E2=80=99t work. =E2=80=
=9CI am going to do stuff for relationship reasons, even if it costs me 0.5=
% of interest income, or a slightly increased risk of losing my money=E2=80=
=9D is no longer a plausible thing to think. Silicon Valley Bank=E2=80=99s =
VC and tech customers talked lovingly about how good their relationships wi=
th SVB were, after withdrawing all their money. They had fiduciary duties t=
o their own investors to keep their money safe! Relationships didn=E2=80=99=
t matter.
One thing that I would say is that if this is right and you take it serious=
ly, then it is pretty bad news for US regional banks. =E2=80=9CBanking is a=
n inherently fragile business model=E2=80=9D is a thing that people say fro=
m time to time (when there are bank runs), but nobody=C2=A0quite=C2=A0means=
 it. They mean something like =E2=80=9Cfrom a strictly financial perspectiv=
e, looking at a balance sheet that mismatches illiquid long-term assets wit=
h overnight funding, banking is insanely fragile, and the whole business mo=
del of banking is about building long-term relationships with slow-moving p=
rice-insensitive depositors so that the funding is not as short-term, and t=
he business is not as fragile, as it looks.=E2=80=9D But if the relationshi=
p aspect doesn=E2=80=99t work anymore, then banking=C2=A0really is just ext=
remely fragile. Without the relationships, banks are just highly levered in=
vestment funds that make illiquid risky hard-to-value investments using ove=
rnight funding. That can go wrong in lots of ways!
At Bits About Money last week, Patrick McKenzie had a deep dive on Theory 2=
, on =E2=80=9CDeposit franchises as natural hedges.=E2=80=9D He lays out=C2=
=A0why=C2=A0banks thought that they could take a lot of interest-rate risk =
despite their short-term funding; he explains the theory that a deposit fra=
nchise =E2=80=94=C2=A0the relationship that banks have with their customers=
 that allows them to keep deposits even as rates go up =E2=80=94=C2=A0is a =
valuable thing and a natural hedge against rising rates.
  [5]
=C2=A0And he too speculates on why that didn=E2=80=99t work as well as they=
 expected. He is, I think, more pessimistic than I was:

For retail, for a period of years=E2=80=94years!=E2=80=94we took the sweat =
and smiles business, the work of literal decades, and we=E2=80=94for the be=
st of reasons!=E2=80=94said We Do Not Want This Thing. That very valuable t=
hing was, like other valuable things like churches and birthday parties and=
 school, a threat to human life. And so we put it aside. We aggressively re=
trained customers to use digital channels over the branch experience. We pu=
t bankers at six thousand institutions in charge of teaching their loyal pe=
rsonal contacts that you can now do about 80% of your routine banking on th=
eir current mobile app or 95% on Chase=E2=80=99s. And then we were shocked,=
 shocked how many people denied the most compelling reason to use their cur=
rent bank and shown the most compelling reason to bank with Chase switched.=
=C2=A0
With regards to sophisticated customers, the answer is not primarily about =
mobile apps or how difficult it is to wire money out of an account. It is a=
bout businesses making rational decisions to protect their interests using =
the information they had. Sophisticated businesses are induced to bring the=
ir deposit businesses, which frequently include large amounts of uninsured =
deposits, in return for a complex and often bespoke bundle of goods they re=
ceive from their banks. The ability to offer that complex and bespoke bundl=
e is part of the sweat and smiles of building a deposit franchise. =E2=80=
=A6
Why did they suddenly trust their banks less about the near-term availabili=
ty of the bundle? Contagion? Social media? I feel these are misdiagnoses. T=
heir banks suffered from two things: their ability to deliver the bundle wa=
s=C2=A0actually impaired. They had =E2=80=9Cbad facts=E2=80=9D, in lawyer p=
arlance.=C2=A0Insolvency is not a good condition for a bank to be in.
And those bad facts got out quickly, not because of social media and not be=
cause of a cabal but simply because=C2=A0news directly relevant to you rout=
es to you much faster in 2023 than in 2013. There is no one single cause fo=
r that! Media are better and more metrics-driven! Screentime among financia=
l decisionmakers is up! Pervasive always-on internetworking in industries h=
as reached beyond early adopters like tech and caught up with the mass midd=
le like e.g. the community that is New York commercial real estate operator=
s.

The whole relationship aspect of banking is devalued; rational economic dec=
isionmaking based on mark-to-market asset values=C2=A0has become more impor=
tant.=C2=A0This makes banks fragile. What makes banks=C2=A0something other =
than highly levered risky investment funds is their relationships, and that=
 support is weakening.=C2=A0
Elsewhere at Substack, here is Byrne Hobart on =E2=80=9C The Relationship-T=
ransactional-Relationship Business Cycle,=E2=80=9D which is I suppose more =
optimistic:
Transaction economics include the flow of object-level decisions=E2=80=94do=
 we buy this Google click, spin up that EC2 instance, or accept this Stripe=
 transaction=E2=80=94and a stock of expectations and trust slowly built up =
on both sides. It's essentially a form of reputational capital, and a compa=
ny that's betting most of its revenue or operations on a counterparty that =
they can't have a conversation with is, in some abstract sense, undercapita=
lized.

