10px;">
<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">People are worried about oil stock buybacks</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is a theory you could have:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The world runs on oil right now, deman=
d for oil is high, the price of oil is high, and getting oil out of the gro=
und is lucrative.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">In X years =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0pick a number =E2=80=94=C2=A0the world will not run on oil, bec=
ause the environmental effects of burning oil are bad, and eventually, thro=
ugh some combination of better green-energy technology, consumer demand and=
 government regulation, the world will stop burning oil.</li>=09<li style=
=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Therefore the oil-drilling business will produce a=
 series of cash flows that is large now and will, over the next X years, de=
cline to zero.</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You don=E2=80=99t have to believe this theory,=
 but something like it seems to be pretty=C2=A0popular. In particular, envi=
ronmental, social and governance investors often express some version of th=
is; they talk about the need to transition to green energy and question the=
 long-term viability of fossil fuels.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I suspect that many oil-and-gas executives and=
 investors <em>don=E2=80=99t</em>=C2=A0believe this theory, but what if the=
y do?=C2=A0If you are the chief executive officer of an oil company, and yo=
u believe this, what should you=C2=A0<em>do=C2=A0</em>about it? What is the=
 best way to create long-term value for your shareholders? Here are=C2=A0th=
ree imaginable answers:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Do what you=E2=80=99ve always done.=
=C2=A0Drill lots of oil, acquire new leases, explore the deep ocean,=C2=A0m=
ake long-term investments in drilling technology, keep being an oil company=
, hope it all works out.=C2=A0</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Piv=
ot to renewables.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"=
color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px;=
 border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; backgr=
ound-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a> Drill oil for now, but make your long-term investments in green energy=
; build wind farms or drill geothermal wells=C2=A0or whatever, so that in X=
 years, when the world stops using oil, you will be able to sell whatever i=
t <em>does=C2=A0</em>use.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Drill th=
e oil you=E2=80=99ve got, but plan for decline. Stop making lots of new lon=
g-term investments in oil fields. Maximize current cash flow, and spend it =
on stock buybacks. Eventually, in X years, your cash flows will be zero, an=
d you will close up shop gracefully. But in the meantime there is money com=
ing in, and rather than waste it on drilling new oil fields, you give it ba=
ck to shareholders.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Answer 1 seems=C2=A0<em>wrong</em>, on this th=
eory: If you make long-term oil investments, and oil is doomed in the long =
term, then your investments are wasteful. You are taking profits that belon=
g to shareholders and wasting them on inertia.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Answer 2 seems fine! The idea here is that you=
 are an=C2=A0<em>energy=C2=A0</em>company, not an=C2=A0<em>oil=C2=A0</em>co=
mpany, and your expertise in energy makes you best positioned to find the e=
nergy of the future.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; ba=
ckground-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a>=C2=A0You have geologists and engineers and energy economists and a lot=
 of money; you might be better at developing green energy than some inexper=
ienced green-energy startup would be. I think this is=C2=A0<em>debatable=C2=
=A0</em>=E2=80=94=C2=A0if you are an oil-company CEO, and you grew up aroun=
d oil, you might be biased against green tech and more comfortable with oil=
 =E2=80=94=C2=A0but certainly possible.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Answer 3 also seems fine! The idea here is tha=
t your company got into business, 100 years ago or whatever, to do a thing:=
 drill oil. You did the thing successfully and it made a lot of money. Now =
the money pours in, but the thing is in decline; there is a natural lifespa=
n to your business, and the end is visible. Rather than fight embarrassingl=
y against the end, you take the cash that is still coming in and you give i=
t to your shareholders.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" sty=
le=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width=
: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; =
background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What do they do with it? Buy groceries or yach=
ts, I suppose, but=C2=A0<em>they=C2=A0</em>could also invest it. They could=
 invest it in green energy companies? Here the idea is that=C2=A0<em>other=
=C2=A0</em>companies =E2=80=94=C2=A0green-energy startups, utility companie=
s, I guess=C2=A0oil companies other than you =E2=80=94=C2=A0will be=C2=A0<e=
m>better=C2=A0</em>at building green energy than you are. (Or: The idea is =
that your shareholders will be better at <em>allocating capital to green-en=
ergy projects=C2=A0</em>than you, an oil-company CEO, are.) You are an oil =
company, your employees and equipment and expertise are all optimized for f=
inding and drilling oil, you have no great advantage in building wind farms=
 and a sort of institutional bias against it. Give the money to shareholder=
s and let them fund the best wind farmers <em>they=C2=A0</em>can find, inst=
ead of asking them to trust you to build a wind farm.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway here is a Wall Street Journal report ab=
out <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31413786.26643=
3/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy9iaWctb2lsLWhhcy0xNTAtYmlsbGlvbi1pb=
i1jYXNoLWFuZC1pbnZlc3RvcnMtd2FudC1hLXNoYXJlLWI1Y2RlYTM1P21vZD1ocF9sZWFkX3Bv=
czE/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa962dafa" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"=
itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none=
 !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border=
-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> how oil-and-gas shareholder=
s want Answer 3</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Oil-and-gas companies have built up a mountain=
 of cash with few precedents in recent history. Wall Street has a few ideas=
 on how to spend it=E2=80=94and new drilling isn=E2=80=99t near the top of =
the list. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Even as an uncertain economic outlook has weig=
hed on crude in 2023, making the energy sector the S&amp;P 500=E2=80=99s wo=
rst performer, cash has continued flowing. Companies that previously chased=
 growth and funneled money into speculative drilling investments, weighing =
down their stocks, have instead tried to appease Wall Street by boosting di=
vidends and repurchasing shares.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The cash has helped make up for stock prices t=
hat often seesaw alongside volatile commodity markets. Steady returns also =
buoy an industry with an uncertain long-term outlook as governments, market=
s and the global economy gradually shift toward cleaner energy.=C2=A0=E2=80=
=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">President Biden has called on producers to ram=
p up output in a bid to lower prices at the pump. =E2=80=9CThese balance sh=
eets make clear that there is nothing stopping oil companies from boosting =
production except their own decision to pad wealthy shareholder pockets and=
 then sit on whatever is left,=E2=80=9D White House Assistant Press Secreta=
ry Abdullah Hasan said. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CU.S. oil-and-gas producers are less f=
ocused on capital spending than they have been in years,=E2=80=9D said Mark=
 Young, a senior analyst at Evaluate Energy.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The cash buildup owes itself to other factors =
as well. Many companies have paid off debt racked up during growth mode, wh=
en they dug much of the top-tier territory for wells. While some companies =
have pledged huge sums to carbon-capture technology or hydrogen production,=
 clean-energy investment has been slowed by lower expected returns and the =
wait for yet-to-be-finalized regulations in Mr. Biden=E2=80=99s climate pac=
kage.=C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I should add that, like, pure-play wind-farm c=
ompanies might have another advantage over oil companies in building wind f=
arms: Their cost of capital might be lower. ESG=C2=A0investors tend to rewa=
rd companies with good ESG scores (like green-energy companies)=C2=A0and pe=
nalize companies with bad ESG scores (like oil companies). This can have th=
e (<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31413786.266433=
/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYXFyLmNvbS9JbnNpZ2h0cy9QZXJzcGVjdGl2ZXMvVmlydHVlLWlzLWl0cy=
1Pd24tUmV3YXJkLU9yLU9uZS1NYW5zLUNlaWxpbmctaXMtQW5vdGhlci1NYW5zLUZsb29y/607f=
07ceef4b8524a319a23cB102c94c9" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscop=
e" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !import=
ant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-=
style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">intended</a>) result of lowering the=
 cost of capital of green companies (lots of ESG investors want to buy thei=
r stock) and raising the cost of capital of polluting companies (nobody wan=
ts their stock). We <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/clic=
k/31413786.266433/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzL=
zIwMjMtMDMtMjIvc2lsaWNvbi12YWxsZXktYmFuay1yYW4tb3V0LW9mLW1vbmV5P2NtcGlkPUJC=
RDA1MDgyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGV=
yJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDUwOCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a31=
9a23cBe984c17a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_b=
lank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bot=
tom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; b=
ackground-color: #ccc;"> talked a few weeks ago</a> about a paper on =E2=80=
=9C<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31413786.266433=
/aHR0cHM6Ly9wYXBlcnMuc3Nybi5jb20vc29sMy9wYXBlcnMuY2ZtP2Fic3RyYWN0X2lkPTQzNT=
kyODI/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB6b6bd9cf" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Counterproductive Sustai=
nable Investing: The Impact Elasticity of Brown and Green Firms</a>,=E2=80=
=9D by Samuel Hartzmark and Kelly Shue, arguing that this has the effect of=
=C2=A0<em>making polluting companies more short-term-focused:=C2=A0</em>If =
your cost of capital is high, near-term projects are worth relatively more =
and long-term projects are worth relatively less, so you will focus on the =
short term. Hartzmark and Shue argue that in particular this means that pol=
luting oil companies who get little love from ESG investors will decide to =
drill more oil to maximize short-term cash flows, but it does also suggest =
that polluting oil companies might=C2=A0decide to do less oil=C2=A0<em>expl=
oration=C2=A0</em>and other long-term oil-focused investment, and spend mor=
e of their cash flows on stock buybacks. Your model could be something like=
 =E2=80=9CESG lowers the cost of capital of green firms and raises the cost=
 of capital of polluting firms, to encourage green firms to invest more for=
 the long term and encourage polluting firms <em>not=C2=A0</em>to plan to s=
tick around.=E2=80=9D And then a lot of stock buybacks from oil firms would=
 be a reasonable ESG outcome.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I should also say that the specific story here=
 =E2=80=94=C2=A0oil companies are buying back stock rather than drilling mo=
re wells =E2=80=94=C2=A0does not=C2=A0<em>require=C2=A0</em>either an ESG p=
erspective or a long-term view that oil is on the decline. =E2=80=9CLast ti=
me oil prices were high, oil companies overinvested in drilling, and then p=
rices crashed and investors lost money=E2=80=9D is also a perfectly reasona=
ble explanation.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One thing that I think, though,=C2=A0when peop=
le get angry about stock buybacks generally, is that there are probably a l=
ot of industries like this? =E2=80=9CWe do a business, it makes money, we h=
ave a lot of money, but eventually this business will end and we won=E2=80=
=99t be good at whatever replaces it, so we might as well give the money ba=
ck to shareholders so <em>they=C2=A0</em>can recycle it, instead of na=C3=
=AFvely=C2=A0reinvesting in a business that can=E2=80=99t last forever,=E2=
=80=9D is probably the right way to think about things a lot of the time!</=
p>
