<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">ESG M&amp;A</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is a basic dynamic in hostile mergers and=
 acquisitions:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">A buyer offers to buy a target for a =
premium to its current share price.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;=
">The target=E2=80=99s board of directors says =E2=80=9Cno, that undervalue=
s our company, sure that offer is higher than our current stock price but o=
ur long-term value is much higher=C2=A0than that.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</li>=09<li=
 style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Maybe the board is right! Maybe it is defend=
ing its shareholders from an opportunistic lowball bid.</li>=09<li style=3D=
"margin-bottom: 5px;">Or maybe it=E2=80=99s wrong! Maybe the directors and =
executives just want to keep their prestigious well-paid jobs, so they are =
rejecting a bid that is good for shareholders. But they know they can=E2=80=
=99t=C2=A0<em>say=C2=A0</em>that, so they say that the bid undervalues the =
company.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And then everyone argues about it. And the arg=
ument is essentially financial: Does the target board have a plan for the c=
ompany that will make it worth more than the buyer=E2=80=99s bid, or not?</=
p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusi=
ness.com/click/31413786.266433/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9u=
L2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTktMDgtMTkvbWF4aW1pemUtc2hhcmVob2xkZXItdmFsdWUtdG9wLWNlb3M=
tbWlnaHQtYmUtb3B0aW5nLW91dD9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNTA4MjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaX=
VtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzA1MDgmdXRtX2NhbXBha=
WduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB6e9193eb" itemprop=3D"StoryLink=
" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-d=
ecoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: =
#000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> essential fe=
ature of =E2=80=9Cstakeholder capitalism=E2=80=9D</a> is that it=C2=A0<em>g=
ives boards and executives more freedom</em>. If a company=E2=80=99s job is=
 not just to maximize financial returns to shareholders, but also to do goo=
d for the environment and workers and customers, then anytime the sharehold=
ers say =E2=80=9Cwe want you to do X,=E2=80=9D and the board doesn=E2=80=99=
t like X, it can say =E2=80=9Cwell that would be bad for workers.=E2=80=9D =
And the if workers say =E2=80=9Cwe want you to do Y,=E2=80=9D and the board=
 doesn=E2=80=99t like Y, it can say =E2=80=9Cwell that would be bad for sha=
reholders.=E2=80=9D There=E2=80=99s always=C2=A0<em>some=C2=A0</em>constitu=
ency that will like something, and some constituency that won=E2=80=99t, an=
d=C2=A0<em>the board gets to choose which constituency counts</em>. There i=
s no single standard to hold the board accountable to; the board just choos=
es which stakeholders matter for any particular decision, so it can make th=
e decision that it wants.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Environmental, social and governance investing=
 is not quite like that: ESG criteria tend to be imposed=C2=A0<em>by shareh=
olders</em>, so a company that pursues ESG goals is giving (many of) its sh=
areholders what they want. Still, to the extent there are trade-offs betwee=
n financial returns and ESG criteria, the directors and executives, rather =
than the shareholders, will often in practice be the people making those tr=
ade-offs. =E2=80=9CWe decided to abandon a profitable project we didn=E2=80=
=99t like because it was bad ESG,=E2=80=9D=C2=A0the board will say, or =E2=
=80=9Cwe decided not to abandon a polluting project that we did like becaus=
e it was good for profits.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0Shareholders can of course push ba=
ck =E2=80=94=C2=A0ESG-focused shareholders can say =E2=80=9Cno, abandon tha=
t polluting project, it=E2=80=99s bad for ESG,=E2=80=9D=C2=A0or non-ESG-foc=
used shareholders can say =E2=80=9Cno, keep the polluting project because i=
t=E2=80=99s profitable=E2=80=9D=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0but the board (1) gets =
to decide and (2) can always point to some=C2=A0<em>shareholder-friendly=C2=
=A0</em>rationale for whatever decision it makes.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What this means is that, in hostile M&amp;A, a=
 board can now reject an offer=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>only on the grounds t=
hat it is too low, but=C2=A0<em>also=C2=A0</em>on the grounds that it not E=
SG enough. The=C2=A0Wall Street Journal=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.b=
loombergbusiness.com/click/31413786.266433/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRp=
Y2xlcy9lbnZpcm9ubWVudGFsLWlzc3Vlcy1jb21wbGljYXRlLWdsZW5jb3Jlcy0yMy1iaWxsaW9=
uLW1lcmdlci1maWdodC03ZGY4ZTk2YT9tb2Q9aHBfbGVhZF9wb3M0/607f07ceef4b8524a319a=
23cB2e394a57" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_bla=
nk" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-botto=
m-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; bac=
kground-color: #ccc;">reported on Friday</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Mining company Glencore=E2=80=99s=C2=A0roughly=
 $23 billion offer for Teck Resources of Canada has injected a new variable=
 into the calculus for big global deal making: ESG.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Usually, the stumbling blocks to a big deal in=
volve some combination of price, control or strategic fit. Teck, however, i=
s also publicly raising environmental, social and governance issues in its =
refusal so far to engage with Glencore about a potential tie-up.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Teck has rejected Glencore=E2=80=99s offer in =
part because it doesn=E2=80=99t want exposure to Glencore=E2=80=99s coal bu=
siness. It also raised concerns about Glencore=E2=80=99s oil-trading busine=
ss and what it said are potential geopolitical risks in certain countries w=
here Glencore operates.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In a presentation to investors laying out its =
rationale for rejecting Glencore=E2=80=99s offer, Teck cited its higher ran=
king in some ESG indexes relative to Glencore=E2=80=99s, pointing to a =E2=
=80=9Csignificant ESG misalignment=E2=80=9D between the two companies, acco=
rding to one slide.=C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Is Teck rejecting this deal because the price =
is too low for shareholders? Because the deal is not ESG enough for shareho=
lders? Or because the deal is not what the executives personally want? Now =
there are=C2=A0<em>three=C2=A0</em>possibilities.<a class=3D"footnote-index=
" href=3D"#footnote-4" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impo=
rtant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-botto=
m-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display=
: inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a></p>
<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Banks</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusin=
ess.com/click/31413786.266433/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL=
2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDUtMDQvbm9ib2R5LXRydXN0cy10aGUtYmFua3Mtbm93P2NtcGlkPUJC=
RDA1MDgyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGV=
yJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDUwOCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a31=
9a23cBaefa17c4" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_b=
lank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bot=
tom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; b=
ackground-color: #ccc;">  talked last Thursday</a> about two theories of ba=
nking, which I called Theory 1 and Theory 2. Theory 1 is that banks borrow =
short to lend long: Bank deposits are short-term funding, they get paid a v=
ariable market rate of interest, and they can disappear overnight if deposi=
tors worry about a bank=E2=80=99s stability or just get a better deal elsew=
here. Theory 2 is that banks actually borrow long to lend long: Bank deposi=
ts are part of a long-term relationship, and much of what banks do =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0build branches, cross-sell products, offer ATMs and online banking=
 =E2=80=94=C2=A0is designed to make those deposits sticky, so that their co=
st=C2=A0<em>doesn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0</em>go up when interest rates go up. Theo=
ry 2 is the traditional theory of banking; it=E2=80=99s why there are branc=
hes. Theory 1 is the standard theory of modern capital markets; it=E2=80=99=
s why, when Silicon Valley Bank failed due to taking too much interest-rate=
 risk, lots of people were like =E2=80=9Chow did they not see that coming=
=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cwhy didn=E2=80=99t they hedge?=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Part of my goal on Thursday was to try to answ=
er those questions, to suggest=C2=A0that Theory 2 really is kind of how ban=
ks (and bank regulators) think about the problem. (=E2=80=9CWhy didn=E2=80=
=99t they hedge their interest-rate risk?=E2=80=9D Well, they had long-dura=
tion liabilities, in the form of deposits, and they matched them with long-=
duration assets, in the form of Treasury and agency bonds, so they=C2=A0<em=
>were=C2=A0</em>hedged; they just got the duration of their deposits wrong.=
)</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And part of my goal was to=C2=A0think about wh=
y Theory 2 stopped working in 2023, why deposits=C2=A0<em>weren=E2=80=99t=
=C2=A0</em>sticky, why banks like Silicon Valley Bank and First Republic Ba=
nk faced massive runs and disappeared when rates went up. My speculations i=
ncluded better availability of information (bank deposits used to be sticky=
 in part because it was harder to pay attention to them), a more widespread=
 mark-to-market financial culture, the hangover of 2008, and the decline of=
 relationship businesses generally:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In a world of electronic communica=
tion and global supply chains and work-from-home and the gig economy, busin=
ess relationships are less sticky and =E2=80=9CI am going to go into my ban=
k branch and shake the hand of the manager and trust her with my life savin=
gs=E2=80=9D doesn=E2=80=99t work. =E2=80=9CI am going to do stuff for relat=
ionship reasons, even if it costs me 0.5% of interest income, or a slightly=
 increased risk of losing my money=E2=80=9D is no longer a plausible thing =
to think. Silicon Valley Bank=E2=80=99s VC and tech customers talked loving=
ly about how good their relationships with SVB were, after withdrawing all =
their money. They had fiduciary duties to their own investors to keep their=
 money safe! Relationships didn=E2=80=99t matter.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One thing that I would say is that if this is =
right and you take it seriously, then it is pretty bad news for US regional=
 banks. =E2=80=9CBanking is an inherently fragile business model=E2=80=9D i=
s a thing that people say from time to time (when there are bank runs), but=
 nobody=C2=A0<em>quite=C2=A0</em>means it. They mean something like =E2=80=
=9Cfrom a strictly financial perspective, looking at a balance sheet that m=
ismatches illiquid long-term assets with overnight funding, banking is insa=
nely fragile, and the whole business model of banking is about building lon=
g-term relationships with slow-moving price-insensitive depositors so that =
the funding is not as short-term, and the business is not as fragile, as it=
 looks.=E2=80=9D But if the relationship aspect doesn=E2=80=99t work anymor=
e, then banking=C2=A0<em>really is just extremely fragile</em>. Without the=
 relationships, banks are just highly levered investment funds that make il=
liquid risky hard-to-value investments using overnight funding. That can go=
 wrong in lots of ways!</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">At Bits About Money last week, Patrick McKenzi=
e had a deep dive on Theory 2, on =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://link.mail.blo=
ombergbusiness.com/click/31413786.266433/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYml0c2Fib3V0bW9uZX=
kuY29tL2FyY2hpdmUvZGVwb3NpdC1mcmFuY2hpc2VzLWFzLW5hdHVyYWwtaGVkZ2VzLw/607f07=
ceef4b8524a319a23cB4dabd6a6" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope"=
 target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importan=
t; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-st=
yle: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Deposit franchises as natural hedges</=
a>.=E2=80=9D He lays out=C2=A0<em>why=C2=A0</em>banks thought that they cou=
ld take a lot of interest-rate risk despite their short-term funding; he ex=
plains the theory that a deposit franchise =E2=80=94=C2=A0the relationship =
that banks have with their customers that allows them to keep deposits even=
 as rates go up =E2=80=94=C2=A0is a valuable thing and a natural hedge agai=
nst rising rates.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-5" style=3D"=
color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px;=
 border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; backgr=
ound-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[5]</span>
</a>=C2=A0And he too speculates on why that didn=E2=80=99t work as well as =
they expected. He is, I think, more pessimistic than I was:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">For retail, for a period of years=E2=80=94year=
s!=E2=80=94we took the sweat and smiles business, the work of literal decad=
es, and we=E2=80=94for the best of reasons!=E2=80=94said We Do Not Want Thi=
s Thing. That very valuable thing was, like other valuable things like chur=
ches and birthday parties and school, a threat to human life. And so we put=
 it aside. We aggressively retrained customers to use digital channels over=
 the branch experience. We put bankers at six thousand institutions in char=
ge of teaching their loyal personal contacts that you can now do about 80% =
of your routine banking on their current mobile app or 95% on Chase=E2=80=
=99s. And then we were shocked, shocked how many people denied the most com=
pelling reason to use their current bank and shown the most compelling reas=
on to bank with Chase switched.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">With regards to sophisticated customers, the a=
nswer is not primarily about mobile apps or how difficult it is to wire mon=
ey out of an account. It is about businesses making rational decisions to p=
rotect their interests using the information they had. Sophisticated busine=
sses are induced to bring their deposit businesses, which frequently includ=
e large amounts of uninsured deposits, in return for a complex and often be=
spoke bundle of goods they receive from their banks. The ability to offer t=
hat complex and bespoke bundle is part of the sweat and smiles of building =
a deposit franchise. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Why did they suddenly trust their banks less a=
bout the near-term availability of the bundle? Contagion? Social media? I f=
eel these are misdiagnoses. Their banks suffered from two things: their abi=
lity to deliver the bundle was=C2=A0<em>actually impaired</em>. They had =
=E2=80=9Cbad facts=E2=80=9D, in lawyer parlance.=C2=A0<em>Insolvency is not=
 a good condition for a bank to be in.</em></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And those bad facts got out quickly, not becau=
se of social media and not because of a cabal but simply because=C2=A0<em>n=
ews directly relevant to you routes to you much faster in 2023 than in 2013=
</em>. There is no one single cause for that! Media are better and more met=
rics-driven! Screentime among financial decisionmakers is up! Pervasive alw=
ays-on internetworking in industries has reached beyond early adopters like=
 tech and caught up with the mass middle like e.g. the community that is Ne=
w York commercial real estate operators.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The whole relationship aspect of banking is de=
valued; rational economic decisionmaking based on mark-to-market asset valu=
es=C2=A0has become more important.=C2=A0<em>This makes banks fragile</em>. =
What makes banks=C2=A0something other than highly levered risky investment =
funds is their relationships, and that support is weakening.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Elsewhere at Substack, here is Byrne Hobart on=
 =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31413786=
.266433/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cudGhlZGlmZi5jby9hcmNoaXZlL3RoZS1yZWxhdGlvbnNoaXAtdHJ=
hbnNhY3Rpb25hbC1yZWxhdGlvbnNoaXAtYnVzaW5lc3MtY3ljbGUvP3JlZj10aGUtZGlmZi1uZX=
dzbGV0dGVy/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB92117fd4" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemsc=
ope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoratio=
n: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000;=
 border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> The Relationship-Tra=
nsactional-Relationship Business Cycle</a>,=E2=80=9D which is I suppose mor=
e optimistic:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Transaction economics include the =
flow of object-level decisions=E2=80=94do we buy this Google click, spin up=
 that EC2 instance, or accept this Stripe transaction=E2=80=94and a stock o=
f expectations and trust slowly built up on both sides. It's essentially a =
form of reputational capital, and a company that's betting most of its reve=
nue or operations on a counterparty that they can't have a conversation wit=
h is, in some abstract sense, undercapitalized.</p></blockquote>
